PHIL 22209 Philosophies of Environmentalism and Sustainability
(ENST 22209, HMRT 22201, PLSC 22202)
Many of the toughest ethical and political challenges confronting the world today are related to environmental issues: for example, climate change, loss of biodiversity, the unsustainable use of natural resources, pollution and toxic waste, and other threats to the well-being of both present and future generations.  Using both classic and contemporary works, this course will highlight some of the fundamental and unavoidable philosophical questions presented by such environmental issues. Does the environmental crisis demand radically new forms of ethical and political philosophizing and practice?  Must an environmental ethic reject anthropocentrism?  If so, what are the most plausible non-anthropocentric alternatives?  What counts as the proper ethical treatment of non-human animals, living organisms, or ecosystems?  What do the terms ânatureâ and âwildernessâ even mean, and should ânaturalâ environments as such have ethical and/or legal standing?  What fundamental ethical and political perspectives inform such approaches as the âLand Ethic,â ecofeminism, and deep ecology?  Is there a plausible account of environmental justice applicable to both present and future generations?  Are we now in the Anthropocene, and if so, is âadaptationâ the best strategy at this historical juncture?  How can the wild, the rural, and the urban all contribute to a better future for Planet Earth? (A)

Since I was nine, I have been performing XiangSheng, a traditional performing art in Chinese comedy. Through telling ancient Chinese tales, I had insight into the beauty of Chinese culture. Although XiangSheng was originated in China, as I grew to identify myself as a Taiwanese, I noticed that I was involved in the localization of XiangSheng: I started to perform XiangSheng that includes Taiwanese jokes; I helped my troupe to translate archaic Chinese into modern Chinese; I assisted performances for Taiwanese kids who learned XiangSheng; I taught them how to perform in colloquial Taiwanese. 
To me, XiangSheng is not a mere heritage that we inherited from China, but a piece of art that embodied in the spirit of Taiwanese culture; a string that connects the diverse culture in every part of Taiwan;  a crystal ball in which I can see possibities of the coexistence between China and Taiwan,

On the stage, wearing a robe, performing a traditional Chinese instrument, I drew my audience into my world. In my XiangSheng world, there are a pharmacy in old Beijing, a buddihist tower with fourteen monks, and four people on their journey to the West for Buddhist scriptures. 
I have been learning XiangSheng since nine. Through telling old Chinese tales, I started to appreciate ancient Chinese culture; Yet, I found out that as I grew to identify myself as a Tawianese, so did XiangSheng. I once perform a script created by my teacher that contains jokes about Taiwan so many that it could only be understood by Taiwanese. In high school, I also began to translate some archaic Chinese into modern, colloquial Chinese so that people could understand. 
Through XiangSheng, I gained an insight on how Chinese culture crossed Taiwan strait and settled on this island, but at the same time, I also saw how it adjusted itself and fit into Taiwan.

On the stage, wearing a robe, performing a traditional Chinese instrument, I drew my audience into my world. In my XiangSheng world, there are a pharmacy in old Beijing, a buddihist tower with fourteen monks, and four people on their journey to the West for Buddhist scriptures. 
When I was nine, my parents sent me to Hanlin to learn about XiangSheng because they wanted to become a cultured Chinese. As time went by, I learned to appreciate the beauty of Chinese and XiangSheng is the bridge connecting me and my root. Yet, there was more than that. Later on, I began to translate the archaic Chinese into modern, colloquial Chinese while my peers included Hakka and other Taiwanese culture into XiangSheng. 
In my teacherâs eyes, I saw how old Chinese crossed Taiwan strait to preserve Chinese culture; in my parentsâ eyes, I saw how elder Taiwanese want to connect themselves with their ancestors/roots through Chinese culture; in the mirror, I saw how new Taiwanese form our own culture identity.

I want to front the essence of the knowlede, east and west, past and future, and learn from the most aspiring, ambitious people from worldwide.
